{% block containment %}
## 🚨 Containment Steps – SQL Injection Response

> **⚡ Execute all phases in order. Tick every checkbox. Escalate to {{ dba_contact | default("the on-call DBA") }} and SOC lead immediately if data exfiltration is confirmed.**

---

### 🔴 Phase 1 · Immediate Triage & Traffic Block `(T+0 → T+10 min)`

> Goal: Stop the attack vector and preserve evidence before any remediation.

- [ ] **Block attacker IP `{{ source_ip | default("<source_ip>") }}` at WAF / firewall**
  Apply DROP rule for all HTTP/HTTPS traffic from `{{ source_ip | default("<source_ip>") }}`.
  Duration: `{{ block_duration | default("3600") }}s`. Rollback tag: `unblock_sqli_{{ source_ip | default("ip") }}`.

  ```bash
  # iptables (web server host)
  iptables -I INPUT -s {{ source_ip | default("<source_ip>") }} -j DROP
  # WAF CLI (ModSecurity example)
  modsec-ctl block-ip {{ source_ip | default("<source_ip>") }} {{ block_duration | default("3600") }}
  ```

- [ ] **Capture full HTTP request/response for evidence**
  Extract the raw payload from WAF / access logs before log rotation:

  ```bash
  grep "{{ source_ip | default("<source_ip>") }}" {{ access_log_path | default("/var/log/nginx/access.log") }} \
    > /tmp/sqli_evidence_{{ source_ip | default("attacker") }}_$(date +%s).log
  ```

- [ ] **Preserve database slow-query / error logs**
  ```bash
  # MySQL
  cp /var/log/mysql/error.log /tmp/mysql_error_$(date +%s).log
  mysqldumpslow -s c /var/log/mysql/slow.log | head -30 > /tmp/slow_queries.log
  # PostgreSQL
  cp /var/log/postgresql/postgresql-*.log /tmp/pg_evidence_$(date +%s)/
  ```

- [ ] **Identify and record the SQLi payload** – Sanitise and document the observed payload:
  > Payload sample: `{{ payload_sample | default("' OR '1'='1'; -- (or similar)") }}`

- [ ] **Check for concurrent sessions from `{{ source_ip | default("<source_ip>") }}`** – Kill any active DB sessions from the attacker:
  ```sql
  -- MySQL
  SELECT id, user, host, command, info
  FROM information_schema.processlist
  WHERE host LIKE '{{ source_ip | default("%") }}%';
  -- Kill active sessions: KILL QUERY <id>;
  -- PostgreSQL
  SELECT pid, usename, application_name, client_addr, state, query
  FROM pg_stat_activity
  WHERE client_addr = '{{ source_ip | default("<source_ip>") }}';
  -- Terminate: SELECT pg_terminate_backend(pid);
  ```

- [ ] **Put application endpoint into maintenance mode** – Temporarily take `{{ target_url | default("the affected endpoint") }}` offline to stop further exploitation:
  ```bash
  # Nginx – return 503
  location {{ target_url | default("/api/") }} {
      return 503 "Maintenance – Please try again later";
  }
  nginx -s reload
  ```

{% if escalate_to_ciso | default(false) %}
- [ ] **🔴 Escalate to CISO** – Data breach risk confirmed. Notify CISO at `{{ ciso_contact | default("ciso@phantomnet.local") }}` immediately.
{% endif %}

- [ ] **Send `{{ alert_level | default("HIGH") }}` alert to SOC and DBA**
  Message: *"SQLi attempt on `{{ target_url | default("<endpoint>") }}` from `{{ source_ip | default("<source_ip>") }}`. DB: `{{ db_engine | default("Unknown") }}`/`{{ db_name | default("<db>") }}`. WAF mode: `{{ waf_mode | default("detection") }}`."*

---

### 🛡️ Phase 2 · WAF Review & Hardening `(T+10 → T+45 min)`

> Goal: Ensure WAF rules catch the attack pattern and switch to prevention mode.

#### 2a. WAF Rule Audit

- [ ] **Review WAF logs for the attack window** – Pull WAF event log for the last `{{ audit_period_hours | default(48) }}` hours:
  ```bash
  # ModSecurity (Apache/Nginx)
  grep -E "id:[0-9]+" /var/log/modsecurity/modsec_audit.log | \
    grep "{{ source_ip | default("<source_ip>") }}" | head -50

  # AWS WAF – via CLI
  aws wafv2 get-sampled-requests \
    --web-acl-arn <arn> --rule-metric-name SQLInjectionRule \
    --scope REGIONAL --time-window StartTime=$(date -d '-48 hours' +%s),EndTime=$(date +%s) \
    --max-items 100
  ```

- [ ] **Identify which WAF rules fired (or should have fired)**
  - Current WAF vendor: `{{ waf_vendor | default("None / Unknown") }}`
  - Current mode: `{{ waf_mode | default("detection") }}` → **Target: `prevention`**
  - Check if OWASP CRS rule set `942xxx` (SQL Injection) is active

- [ ] **Switch WAF to PREVENTION mode** – If WAF is currently in `detection` mode, block mode must be enabled immediately:
  ```bash
  # ModSecurity – set SecRuleEngine to On
  sed -i 's/SecRuleEngine DetectionOnly/SecRuleEngine On/' /etc/modsecurity/modsecurity.conf
  nginx -s reload   # or: apachectl graceful

  # Verify
  grep "SecRuleEngine" /etc/modsecurity/modsecurity.conf
  # Expected: SecRuleEngine On
  ```

- [ ] **Create/tune a custom WAF rule for the observed payload pattern**
  ```bash
  # ModSecurity custom rule example
  cat >> /etc/modsecurity/custom_rules.conf << 'EOF'
  SecRule ARGS "@detectSQLi" \
    "id:9000001,phase:2,deny,status:403,\
    log,msg:'Custom SQLi block - {{ source_ip | default("attacker") }}',\
    tag:'sqli_attempt'"
  EOF
  nginx -s reload
  ```

- [ ] **Verify WAF blocks the payload** – Replay a sanitised version of the payload against the WAF in a test environment to confirm the rule fires:
  ```bash
  curl -v -X {{ http_method | default("GET") }} \
    "{{ target_url | default("http://localhost/api/test") }}?id=1'+OR+'1'='1" \
    -H "X-Forwarded-For: 127.0.0.1"
  # Expected response: 403 Forbidden
  ```

- [ ] **Enable WAF rate-limiting** – Add a rate-limit rule for the targeted endpoint to throttle scanning:
  ```nginx
  # Nginx rate limit
  limit_req_zone $binary_remote_addr zone=api_limit:10m rate=10r/s;
  location {{ target_url | default("/api/") }} {
      limit_req zone=api_limit burst=20 nodelay;
  }
  ```

- [ ] **Review and update WAF allow-list / deny-list** – Ensure `{{ source_ip | default("<source_ip>") }}` is in the permanent deny list.

#### 2b. Application-Level Firewall Review

- [ ] **Verify Content-Security-Policy (CSP) headers** are set on all responses from `{{ target_url | default("<endpoint>") }}`.
- [ ] **Confirm X-Content-Type-Options and X-Frame-Options headers** are present.
- [ ] **Check CORS policy** – Ensure API does not allow arbitrary origins that could facilitate cross-origin SQLi exploitation.

---

### 🔎 Phase 3 · Input Validation Audit `(T+45 min → T+3 hours)`

> Goal: Find and fix every code path that could accept unsanitised SQL-injectable input.

#### 3a. Vulnerable Endpoint Identification

- [ ] **Map all input vectors on the affected endpoint** – List every query parameter, form field, cookie, and header that flows into a SQL query at `{{ target_url | default("<endpoint>") }}`:

{% if affected_endpoints is defined and affected_endpoints %}
  **Known affected endpoints:**
{% for ep in affected_endpoints %}
  - `{{ ep }}`
{% endfor %}
{% else %}
  ```bash
  # Automated discovery – use a tool like sqlmap in audit mode (non-destructive)
  sqlmap -u "{{ target_url | default("http://app/api/endpoint") }}" \
    --batch --level=3 --risk=1 --technique=BEUSTQ \
    --forms --crawl=3 --output-dir=/tmp/sqlmap_audit_$(date +%s)
  ```
{% endif %}

- [ ] **Trace DB query construction in source code** – Locate every occurrence of raw SQL string concatenation in `{{ app_framework | default("the application") }}` codebase:
  ```bash
  # Search for string concatenation patterns (Python example)
  grep -rn --include="*.py" \
    -E '"SELECT|INSERT|UPDATE|DELETE|FROM|WHERE.*\+|.*%s.*format|f\".*SELECT' \
    app/ | grep -v ".pyc" | grep -v test_

  # JavaScript / Node.js
  grep -rn --include="*.js" \
    -E "query\(.*\+|execute\(.*\+" src/

  # Java
  grep -rn --include="*.java" \
    -E "prepareStatement\(.*\+|createStatement\(\)" src/
  ```

- [ ] **Identify all direct DB query calls bypassing ORM** – Even if an ORM is configured (`orm_in_use: {{ orm_in_use | default(false) }}`), raw query escapes must be found:
  ```bash
  # Django / SQLAlchemy raw queries
  grep -rn --include="*.py" \
    -E "\.raw\(|\.execute\(|cursor\.execute" app/

  # Hibernate native queries
  grep -rn --include="*.java" \
    -E "createNativeQuery|createSQLQuery" src/
  ```

#### 3b. Parameterised Query Enforcement

- [ ] **Replace ALL string-concatenated queries with parameterised statements**
  Every vulnerable query must be converted. Examples:

  ```python
  # ❌ VULNERABLE – Python
  query = "SELECT * FROM users WHERE id = '" + user_id + "'"
  cursor.execute(query)

  # ✅ SAFE – parameterised
  cursor.execute("SELECT * FROM users WHERE id = %s", (user_id,))
  ```

  ```javascript
  // ❌ VULNERABLE – Node.js
  db.query("SELECT * FROM users WHERE id = '" + userId + "'")

  // ✅ SAFE – parameterised
  db.query("SELECT * FROM users WHERE id = ?", [userId])
  ```

  ```java
  // ❌ VULNERABLE – Java JDBC
  String sql = "SELECT * FROM users WHERE id = '" + userId + "'";

  // ✅ SAFE – PreparedStatement
  PreparedStatement ps = conn.prepareStatement(
      "SELECT * FROM users WHERE id = ?");
  ps.setString(1, userId);
  ```

- [ ] **Enforce input type and length validation at controller layer** – Validate all inputs before they reach the data layer:
  - [ ] Integer IDs: enforce `int()` / `parseInt()` cast; reject non-numeric input
  - [ ] String fields: enforce max-length limits matching DB column size
  - [ ] Enum fields: whitelist allowed values; reject anything not in the list
  - [ ] Email fields: validate with RFC-compliant regex before use in query

- [ ] **Enable ORM strict mode** – If `{{ app_framework | default("the framework") }}` supports it, enable strict parameterisation:
  ```python
  # Django – ORM is parameterised by default; audit for .extra() / .raw()
  # SQLAlchemy – use text() with bindparams for any raw SQL:
  from sqlalchemy import text
  result = db.execute(text("SELECT * FROM users WHERE id = :id"), {"id": user_id})
  ```

- [ ] **Add server-side input sanitisation library** – Integrate a SQL injection filter as a defence-in-depth layer:
  ```bash
  # Python
  pip install sqlalchemy-utils bleach
  # Node.js
  npm install validator sqlstring
  # Java
  # Add OWASP ESAPI to pom.xml
  ```

#### 3c. Code Review Checklist

- [ ] **Review all stored procedures** in `{{ db_name | default("the target database") }}` for dynamic SQL construction.
- [ ] **Review error handling** – Ensure DB error messages are not returned to the client (information leakage):
  ```bash
  # Confirm no SQL errors in HTTP responses
  curl -s "{{ target_url | default("http://app/api") }}?id=1'" | grep -iE "syntax|mysql|pg_|ora-|sql"
  # Should return no database error strings
  ```
- [ ] **Check HTTP response codes** – Ensure `500 Internal Server Error` is not leaked on SQLi attempts (replace with `400 Bad Request`).
- [ ] **Verify logging** – All SQLi attempts must be logged to SIEM with full request context (IP, method, URL, payload hash).

---

### 🗄️ Phase 4 · Database Integrity Check & Recovery `(T+3 hours → Close)`

> Goal: Verify what data was accessed or modified and restore DB to a trusted state.

#### 4a. DB Integrity Assessment

- [ ] **Review DB audit / binary logs for the attack window**
  ```sql
  -- MySQL: check binary log for changes around attack time
  SHOW BINARY LOGS;
  mysqlbinlog --start-datetime="{{ detection_time | default("2026-01-01 00:00:00") }}" \
    --stop-datetime="{{ generated_at | default("NOW") }}" \
    /var/log/mysql/mysql-bin.* | grep -E "INSERT|UPDATE|DELETE|DROP|CREATE"

  -- PostgreSQL: check pg_audit log
  grep -E "INSERT|UPDATE|DELETE|DROP" /var/log/postgresql/postgresql-*.log | \
    grep "{{ detection_time | default("today") }}"

  -- MSSQL: query sys.fn_dblog
  SELECT [Current LSN], [Transaction ID], [Operation], [Context], [AllocUnitName]
  FROM fn_dblog(NULL, NULL)
  WHERE [Transaction ID] != '0000:00000000'
    AND [Begin Time] > '{{ detection_time | default("2026-01-01") }}'
  ```

- [ ] **Identify tables potentially accessed or modified**

{% if affected_tables is defined and affected_tables %}
  **Tables flagged for review:**
  | Table Name | Risk Level | Action |
  |------------|-----------|--------|
{% for tbl in affected_tables %}
  | `{{ tbl }}` | 🔴 HIGH | Audit all rows modified since `{{ detection_time | default("detection time") }}` |
{% endfor %}
{% else %}
  ```sql
  -- Identify tables accessed via the injection point
  -- MySQL: check performance_schema events_statements_history
  SELECT event_name, sql_text, rows_affected, timer_start
  FROM performance_schema.events_statements_history_long
  WHERE sql_text LIKE '%{{ db_name | default("target_db") }}%'
    AND timer_start > UNIX_TIMESTAMP('{{ detection_time | default("now") }}') * 1e12
  ORDER BY timer_start DESC LIMIT 50;
  ```
{% endif %}

- [ ] **Check for privilege escalation via SQLi** – Look for any new DB accounts, role changes, or permission grants in the audit log:
  ```sql
  -- MySQL: check user changes
  SELECT * FROM mysql.user ORDER BY password_last_changed DESC LIMIT 20;
  SELECT * FROM information_schema.USER_PRIVILEGES
  WHERE GRANTEE NOT IN ('<list of known accounts>');

  -- PostgreSQL
  SELECT usename, usesuper, usecreatedb, usecreaterole, valuntil
  FROM pg_user ORDER BY usesysid DESC LIMIT 20;
  ```

- [ ] **Scan for web shells or malicious files** – If the DB supports file operations (MySQL `OUTFILE`, MSSQL `xp_cmdshell`), check for dropped files:
  ```bash
  # Check for recently created PHP/ASPX/JSP files in web root
  find {{ web_root | default("/var/www/html") }} -name "*.php" -newer /tmp/sqli_evidence* \
    -exec ls -la {} \; 2>/dev/null
  find {{ web_root | default("/var/www/html") }} \
    \( -name "*.php" -o -name "*.jsp" -o -name "*.aspx" \) \
    -mmin -{{ (audit_period_hours | default(48)) * 60 }} \
    -exec sha256sum {} \; > /tmp/new_webfiles.txt
  ```

- [ ] **Check if `xp_cmdshell` (MSSQL) or `UDF` (MySQL) was enabled** – These allow OS command execution via SQLi:
  ```sql
  -- MSSQL
  SELECT value FROM sys.configurations WHERE name = 'xp_cmdshell';
  -- Should be 0. If 1: EXEC sp_configure 'xp_cmdshell', 0; RECONFIGURE;

  -- MySQL: check for UDFs
  SELECT * FROM mysql.func;
  ```

#### 4b. Data Exfiltration Assessment

- [ ] **Estimate data volume exfiltrated** – Check network egress logs for unusual outbound traffic from `{{ db_host | default("<db_host>") }}` during the attack window:
  ```bash
  # Netflow / pcap analysis
  tcpdump -r /tmp/capture.pcap src host {{ db_host | default("<db_host>") }} \
    -w /tmp/db_egress.pcap
  # Check bytes transferred per connection
  capinfos /tmp/db_egress.pcap
  ```

- [ ] **Assess PII / sensitive data exposure** – Determine if PII (names, emails, SSNs, payment data) was in any accessed tables and trigger breach notification procedures if required.

- [ ] **Review application logs for `UNION SELECT` / `INFORMATION_SCHEMA` queries** – These indicate schema enumeration:
  ```bash
  grep -i -E "union.*select|information_schema|group_concat|load_file|outfile" \
    {{ access_log_path | default("/var/log/nginx/access.log") }} | \
    grep "{{ source_ip | default("<source_ip>") }}"
  ```

#### 4c. DB Restoration & Hardening

- [ ] **Restore from last known-good backup** (if data tampering confirmed)
  ```bash
  # MySQL
  mysql -u root -p {{ db_name | default("target_db") }} < \
    {{ backup_path | default("/backups/db_latest.sql") }}

  # PostgreSQL
  pg_restore -d {{ db_name | default("target_db") }} \
    {{ backup_path | default("/backups/db_latest.dump") }}

  # Verify restore
  mysqlcheck -u root -p --all-databases --check
  ```

- [ ] **Change all database credentials** – Rotate passwords for all DB accounts:
  ```sql
  -- MySQL
  ALTER USER '{{ db_app_user | default("app_user") }}'@'%'
    IDENTIFIED BY '<new_strong_password>';
  FLUSH PRIVILEGES;

  -- PostgreSQL
  ALTER USER {{ db_app_user | default("app_user") }} WITH PASSWORD '<new_strong_password>';
  ```

- [ ] **Apply principle of least privilege** – Audit and tighten DB user permissions. The application user should NOT have:
  - [ ] `FILE` privilege (MySQL) / `pg_read_server_files` (PostgreSQL)
  - [ ] `SUPER` / `DBA` role
  - [ ] `DROP`, `CREATE`, `ALTER` on production tables
  - [ ] `EXECUTE` on stored procedures not required for normal operation

  ```sql
  -- MySQL: revoke dangerous privileges
  REVOKE FILE ON *.* FROM '{{ db_app_user | default("app_user") }}'@'%';
  REVOKE SUPER ON *.* FROM '{{ db_app_user | default("app_user") }}'@'%';
  SHOW GRANTS FOR '{{ db_app_user | default("app_user") }}'@'%';
  ```

- [ ] **Enable DB query auditing** – Ensure all future queries are logged to SIEM:
  ```sql
  -- MySQL: enable general log temporarily
  SET GLOBAL general_log = 'ON';
  SET GLOBAL general_log_file = '/var/log/mysql/general.log';

  -- PostgreSQL: ensure log_statement = 'all' in postgresql.conf
  -- pg_audit extension is preferred for production
  ```

- [ ] **Create incident ticket in `{{ ticket_system | default("Jira") }}`** – Project: `{{ ticket_project | default("SEC") }}`
  Summary: *"SQLi Attempt: `{{ source_ip | default("<source_ip>") }}` → `{{ target_url | default("<endpoint>") }}` – DB: `{{ db_engine | default("Unknown") }}`/`{{ db_name | default("<db>") }}`"*

{% if pen_test_required | default(false) %}
- [ ] **Schedule follow-up penetration test** – A full DAST/penetration test of `{{ target_url | default("the application") }}` must be completed within 14 days.
{% endif %}

- [ ] **Schedule post-incident review** – 48-hour debrief with AppSec, DBA (`{{ dba_contact | default("DBA team") }}`), and SOC.

